summary: This kid tries to prove point and I put him on the ground faster than you could say endgame. The only time tony stark was ever...
body:
So my friend said he thinks Ironman is annoying and I don’t think he realizes who he is talking to.

This kid tries to prove point and I put him on the ground faster than you could say endgame. The only time tony stark was ever annoying was never he thinks he could win this argument still and he still doesn’t realize that I have an insurmountable amount of love for tony stark. For gods sake this is my background:

He says that Ironman only works for himself he doesn’t help others and I reminded him that the person who originally called stark that( Steve Rogers) now calls him, “Earths best defender” he is kind and amazing and does not deserve to be called “ annoying”. When he found a kid who was struggling to really make a difference, he gave him a knee suit and helped him make a difference. He struggling through mental illness and never stopped trying to save everyone. “He sided with the government during civil war”, he was siding with them because he had heard the stories of the people who had died while they were saving places such as sokovia and New York and was trying to prevent people from dying like that again and if any one else wants to fight me on this I will

summary: I don’t know when exactly Marvel walked back their policy of being able to use “damn” and “hell,” but it made for some...
caption: I don’t know when exactly Marvel walked back their policy of being able to use “damn” and “hell,” but it made for some extraordinarily awkward dialogue, like this panel from 1994’s War Machine #8, by Scott Benson, Len Kaminski, Gabriel Gecko and Pam Eklund.

reblog.comment: I don’t know when exactly Marvel walked back their policy of being able to use “damn” and “hell,” but it made for some extraordinarily awkward dialogue, like this panel from 1994’s War Machine #8, by Scott Benson, Len Kaminski, Gabriel Gecko and Pam Eklund.

trail.content_raw: I don’t know when exactly Marvel walked back their policy of being able to use “damn” and “hell,” but it made for some extraordinarily awkward dialogue, like this panel from 1994’s War Machine #8, by Scott Benson, Len Kaminski, Gabriel Gecko and Pam Eklund.
trail.content: I don’t know when exactly Marvel walked back their policy of being able to use “damn” and “hell,” but it made for some extraordinarily awkward dialogue, like this panel from 1994’s War Machine #8, by Scott Benson, Len Kaminski, Gabriel Gecko and Pam Eklund.
